# Loom

Loom is a literate programming framework. You write a document — prose and code together, in the order that reads best — and Loom tangles it, composing the code into real source files. The prose is not documentation wrapped around the code but part of the program: the layer a person reads to learn what the code does and why.

This book is written in Loom, in the framework's own source, and it is the framework's only specification: the design notes that once sat apart from the code now live here, in the chapters that describe it, where they cannot drift. `loom weave` renders the book as the website you are reading — every chapter a page, its prose and its code side by side. Read it from the front. It opens with using Loom, then opens the machine, each part building on the one before.

# Table of Content {TOC}

## Part I — Using Loom

You meet Loom the way you use it: by writing a document and watching it become code. This part is the whole surface a person touches, and nothing beneath it. It begins with a single loom and grows to a real project — sections composed with anchors and warps, one narrative spread across many files and languages, a workspace Loom sets up for you, and a command line that drives the rest. By the end you can build with Loom without yet knowing how it works inside.

Part I is not yet written. It is authored last, once the machine it introduces has settled, and folds in the guide that already teaches Loom from a first document up.

## Part II — How a loom becomes code

You have written a loom; this part is what Loom makes of it. It is the short path through the idea at the centre of the framework, and the map for every part that follows.

Loom is a literate-programming language, and a loom weaves three layers into one file. The **Loom syntax** composes the document — the headings, the `::[…]` anchors, and the sinks that name where code lands. The **prose** is the layer a person reads. The **code** is what each section is written in, in that section's own language. The editor serves all three, and tangling acts on the code.

Loom reads the file into a single tree and carries it along a chain of small, total passes: it cuts the text into lines, labels each line, fills in the pieces inside it, and folds the lines into a document of sections. One more pass composes that document into its **product** — the author's code with every `::[…]` anchor resolved to an edge, so a section that names another draws it in. From that one tree Loom serves everything downstream: the tangler writes the product to files, and the editor reads the same tree, a language service to each layer. The rest of the book walks that pipeline one pass at a time.

## Part III — The shape of a loom

A loom is text, but Loom does not work on text. It works on a tree. This part is that tree — the data model every later pass reads and enriches. One foundation underlies every node; on it stand three layers — the tokens inside a line, the lines themselves, and the sections the lines form — and above them the corpus, the modules that import one another.

## Part IV — Reading the text

A loom arrives as plain text, and Loom must read it into the tree the previous part described. This part is that reading — four passes that turn text into a document, and a fifth that follows the document's imports out to its corpus. Each pass is total: it consumes the stream the pass before it produced and never throws.

## Part V — The product

Here the document becomes code. Each section carries the author's code, and each `::[…]` anchor says how that code composes; this part is the pass that reads the one and follows the other. No program stands in between — the anchors already form the composition graph, so the pass reads that graph off the parse and builds the product from it.

## Part VI — Tangling

With the product built, Loom writes it out. This part is the back half of the pipeline. The compiler works out what each consumer needs and hands it a projection; the tangler writes each sink's composed code to disk; and the configuration — itself a loom — supplies the languages, delimiters, and roots that govern the build. A cache underneath keeps the next build fast, and a single catalog names every fault the author can hit.

## Part VII — In the editor

A loom is several languages at once — the Loom syntax, the prose, and the code in each section's language — and this part gives each of them a real editor. Loom projects the document into a tree of virtual files, one language to a file, and hands that tree to the editor through a single plugin and a language server. Every diagnostic maps back to the spot you wrote, and Loom's own mistakes — a malformed tag, an anchor that resolves to nothing — surface beside the code.

## Part VIII — Languages as packages

Loom composes any language, so a language's editor support cannot be built in. It arrives as a package. This part is the contract such a package satisfies and the path it travels into a project: the host lends each service its runtime, so the package ships thin; `loom add` installs it into a store of Loom's own; a registry finds it by language; and the editor loads it on demand. TypeScript is the worked example.

## Part IX — Loom builds Loom

The book closes where it began, with the fact that Loom is written in Loom. This part is the cycle that keeps that honest: the published tool builds the next release, never the in-progress source. Around the cycle sit the pieces that ship it — the command-line program, the bundles that fold each package into one file, the editor extension, the package manifests, and the release that publishes them all.

## Part X — Work in progress

This part is never finished. It holds the framework's active work — each open problem or unbuilt feature as its own loom, written to be worked out in place. Such a loom is not a specification. It opens as prose that states the problem and the shape of the answer, and it is built by amending that same loom with code, refining the prose as the design settles — never by taking it as a plan and writing the code somewhere else. So it travels from idea to implementation as one artifact, and never drifts from what it describes. When a chapter here is done, it graduates to its home part.
